1459":"1459","1425":"1425","about 1424":"omkring 1424","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","about 1440":"omkring 1440","1428":"1428","Gray Friars Church, London, England":"London, England","Herstmonceux, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","London, England":"London, England"},"nl":{"Abt 1395–about 1440":"circa 1395–circa 1440","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1425–1459":"1425–1459","1428–1471":"1428–1471","1395–1440":"1395–1440","Abt 1395":"circa 1395","1459":"1459","1425":"1425","about 1424":"circa 1424","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","about 1440":"circa 1440","1428":"1428","Gray Friars Church, London, England":"London, England","Herstmonceux, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","London, England":"London, England"},"en":{"Abt 1395–about 1440":"about 1395–about 1440","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1425–1459":"1425–1459","1428–1471":"1428–1471","1395–1440":"1395–1440","Abt 1395":"about 1395","1459":"1459","1425":"1425","about 1424":"about 1424","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","about 1440":"about 1440","1428":"1428","Gray Friars Church, London, England":"London, England","Herstmonceux, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan was born about 1395. She married Sir James Fiennes about 1424. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died about 1440, in London, England, at the age of 47, and was buried in London, England."},"et":{"Abt 1395–about 1440":"umbes 1395–umbes 1440","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1425–1459":"1425–1459","1428–1471":"1428–1471","1395–1440":"1395–1440","Abt 1395":"umbes 1395","1459":"1459","1425":"1425","about 1424":"umbes 1424","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","about 1440":"umbes 1440","1428":"1428","Gray Friars Church, London, England":"London, England","Herstmonceux, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1395–about 1440":"noin 1395–noin 1440","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1425–1459":"1425–1459","1428–1471":"1428–1471","1395–1440":"1395–1440","Abt 1395":"noin 1395","1459":"1459","1425":"1425","about 1424":"noin 1424","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","about 1440":"noin 1440","1428":"1428","Gray Friars Church, London, England":"London, England","Herstmonceux, Sussex, England":"Herstmonceux, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1395–about 1440":"environ 1395–environ 1440","1395–1450":"1395–1450","1425–1459":"1425–1459","1428–1471":"1428–1471","1395–1440":"1395–1440","Abt 1395":"environ 1395","1459":"1459","1425":"1425","about 1424":"environ 1424","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","about 1440":"environ 1440","1428":"1428","Gray Friars Church, London, England":"Londres, Angleterre","Herstmonceux, Sussex,